Step 1: Calculate the Current Ratio  
• The Current Ratio is defined as:  
  Current Ratio = Total Current Assets / Total Current Liabilities  
• From the balance sheet, the ending amounts are:  
  Total Current Assets = 9,221,098.50  
  Total Current Liabilities = 378,850.51  
• Compute:  
  Current Ratio = 9,221,098.50 / 378,850.51 ≈ 24.32  

Step 2: Calculate the Inventory Turnover Ratio  
• The Inventory Turnover Ratio is given by:  
  Inventory Turnover Ratio = Cost of Goods Sold (COGS) / Average Inventory  
• Here, the inventory figures available are:  
  Initial Inventory = 0.00  
  Ending Inventory = 203,000.00  
  Average Inventory = (0 + 203,000.00) / 2 = 101,500.00  
• From the income statement, the COGS is:  
  COGS = 1,015,000.00  
• Compute:  
  Inventory Turnover Ratio = 1,015,000.00 / 101,500.00 = 10.00  

Thus, the final results are:  

{
  "solution": {
    "Current Ratio": "24.32",
    "Inventory Turnover Ratio": "10.00"
  }
}
